 to the here and now and thankfully I did recover and focused on helping my team.\r\n\r\nOn the tube home at the end of the event I started to think about the difference between success and failure?  Logically success or failure is based on accurately achieving a goal, an aim or a purpose.  In competitive scenarios the successor is the one who comes closest to achieving a goal, aim or purpose.  With this in mind the first thing we need to do to be successful is clearly understand the goal, aim or purpose.  I realised that I had paid no attention to the point system that has been assigned to the pitches.  How will I ever be successful if I don\'t keep the goal clearly in mind?\r\n\r\nBut perhaps the biggest difference between success and failure is our response to it.  I imagined how my team would have responded if we had been successful.  We would have glowed with pride and smiled with accomplishment.  We would have praised each other on our efforts, quickly forgetting the difficulties that we had faced.  We would have been open to integrating with other participants, taking praise and talking about how and what we had done to achieve our success.\r\nAnd how did we act in failure?  We were outwardly sympathetic towards our team members.  We were introvert, retrospective, critical and analytical.  We wanted to to expose the weeds and acknowledge the areas of weakness.  We made comparisons about the validity of our idea compared with those that were successful, keen to discover the key to their success. \r\n\r\nWe all know that failure is inevitable, it is a part of life.  Some say that failure is the key to success and perhaps that is true but only in so far as you choose to learn from your failure.  If failure has you feeling so hurt and disheartened that you decide not to expose yourself  and give up then it won\'t help you succeed.  With this in mind we must choose our goal, aim or purpose carefully.  If we are passionate about achieving our goal, aim or purpose because we know that it will bring us lasting fulfilment, satisfaction and happiness then we are more likely to learn from our failures allowing them to further motivate us to try again.\r\n\r\nThe best thing we can do to alleviate the suffering we create around failure is to respond to it the same as success.  We can glow with pride and smile with accomplishment because we gave it a try, because without those that try, those that are willing to expose themselves and make themselves vulnerable humanity will not progress.  If we can fail with a smile on our face in the knowledge that we will learn from our mistakes, then we can create a new culture where individuals are inspired to try without fear and stigma of failure.  If in failure we can be equally retrospective and analytical about our strengths and our weaknesses then having identified our strengths we can play a better, stronger hand and we can celebrate our strengths despite failure.\r\n\r\nAnd just as importantly, if in success we can maintain humility, if we reject feelings of superiority, grandiosity and importance and if we respond just as we do in failure then we narrow the gap between success and failure and we highlight the significance and importance of the journey rather than the achievement of a goal, aim or purpose.','The difference between success and failure','','inherit','closed','closed','','463-revision-v1','','','2017-11-29 18:51:27','2017-11-29 18:51:27','',463,'http://blog.calloftheforest.com/463-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(472,1,'2017-11-29 18:51:59','2017-11-29 18:51:59','I recently attended a competitive 2 day event based around creating an investable business opportunity that met UN\'s SDG12 (sustainable development goal)  - responsible consumption and production.  This was an opportunity for me to learn more about business, sustainability in business and to interact with like minded people.\r\n\r\nOnce the event kicked off  I spontaneously decided to pitch my potential business, 